<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="degrees">1. Notes and Degrees (Reading in Numbers)</h2>

<blockquote class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4 py-2 my-4 bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900/20"><strong>Key Point</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">1 = tonic</strong> to understand <strong class="font-semibold">position relationships through numbers 1â€“7</strong>. When the key changes, "1" moves (movable do). The number sequence stays the same.</blockquote>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="what-are-degrees">1.1 What Are Degrees (Movable Do System)</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li>C major: <strong class="font-semibold">1=C 2=D 3=E 4=F 5=G 6=A 7=B</strong>  </li>
<li>D major: <strong class="font-semibold">1=D 2=E 3=F# 4=G 5=A 6=B 7=C#</strong>  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">â™­/â™¯ in degrees</strong> (e.g., â™­3, â™¯4) indicate "half-step shifts".</li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Say the <strong class="font-semibold">1</strong> of your current key out loud, then translate 1â†’2â†’3â€¦ into note names.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="major-minor-degrees">1.2 Major vs. Minor Sequences</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Major</strong>: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 (wholeâ€“wholeâ€“halfâ€“wholeâ€“wholeâ€“wholeâ€“half)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Natural Minor</strong>: 1 2 â™­3 4 5 â™­6 â™­7  </li>
</ul>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">(Harmonic = raised 7, Melodic ascending = raised 6 & 7)</p>

<strong class="font-semibold">Example with D as Tonic</strong>  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">D major: D E <strong class="font-semibold">F#</strong> G A B <strong class="font-semibold">C#</strong>  </p>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">D natural minor: D E <strong class="font-semibold">F</strong> G A <strong class="font-semibold">Bâ™­</strong> <strong class="font-semibold">C</strong></p>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Identify what degree the melodic peak is, then place that degree as the top note in your accompaniment.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="c-d-cheatsheet">1.3 Câ†”D Conversion Cheat Sheet</h3>
<table class="w-full border-collapse my-4 text-sm"><thead><tr><th class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-left">Degree</th><th class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-left">C Major</th><th class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-left">D Major</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">1</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">C</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">D</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">2</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">D</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">E</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">3</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">E</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">F#</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">4</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">F</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">G</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">5</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">G</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">A</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">6</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">A</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">B</td></tr>
<tr><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">7</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">B</td><td class="border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 px-3 py-2">C#</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV (Câ€“Gâ€“Amâ€“F)</strong> in C â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G</strong> in D.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="degree-vs-interval">1.4 Degrees vs. Intervals</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Degrees</strong>: Numbers within a key (1â€“7)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Intervals</strong>: Distance between any two notes (perfect 5th, minor 3rd, etc.)  </li>
</ul>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Use <strong class="font-semibold">degrees for progressions/melodies, intervals for voicings</strong>.</p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="on-fretboard">1.5 Finding Degrees on the Fretboard: Quick Method</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">1. Fix <strong class="font-semibold">1 (tonic)</strong> on 6th or 5th string (e.g., D = 5th string 5th fret / 6th string 10th fret).  </p>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">2. On the same string: <strong class="font-semibold">+2 = 2 â†’ +2 = 3 â†’ +1 = 4 â€¦</strong> (wholeâ€“wholeâ€“halfâ€¦).  </p>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">3. Work backwards from forms that place the desired degree on <strong class="font-semibold">top</strong>.</p>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="chords">2. Chord Basics (Building by Numbers)</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="triads">2.1 Triads</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Major</strong>: 1â€“3â€“5 (sunny)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Minor</strong>: 1â€“â™­3â€“5 (cloudy)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Dim</strong>: 1â€“â™­3â€“â™­5 (anxious)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Aug</strong>: 1â€“3â€“â™¯5 (floating)</li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Play Dâ†’<strong class="font-semibold">Dm</strong>â†’G (change just the 3rd by a half-step) to hear the color shift.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="sevenths">2.2 Seventh Chords</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">V7</strong> = arrow pushing to I (A7â†’D)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">maj7</strong> = dissolves into the same place (Dmaj7)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">m7</strong> = calm depth (Em7)  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">m7â™­5</strong> = bridge tension (BÃ¸)</li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Play <strong class="font-semibold">Aâ†’A7â†’D</strong> to feel the 7th's "arrow effect".

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="symbols">2.3 Reading Symbols (add/sus/slash)</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">add9</strong>: Add color  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">sus4/sus2</strong>: Suspend 3rd temporarily â†’ resolve back to 3  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">D/F#</strong>: Specify bass note (inversion)</li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Oscillate <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Dsus4â€“D</strong> to experience "suspension â†’ resolution".

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="key-roman">3. Keys and Roman Numerals (Transposing by Numbers)</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="diatonic">3.1 Diatonic Chords</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">D major</strong>: D Em F#m G A Bm C#Â°  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">D minor (natural)</strong>: Dm EÂ° F Gm Am (or A) Bâ™­ C</li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Transpose <strong class="font-semibold">Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV</strong> to D â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="tsd">3.2 Function and Cadences</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">T (stable)</strong>: I, vi  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">S (preparation)</strong>: ii, IV  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">D (gravitational pull)</strong>: V, viiÂ°  </li>
</ul>

<strong class="font-semibold">Cadence Examples</strong>:  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Vâ†’I (strong) / IVâ†’I (soft) / Vâ†’vi (deceptive)</p>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Always use <strong class="font-semibold">Vâ†’I</strong> at the start of the chorus to plant a flag.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="guitarist">4. Guitar-Specific</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="voicing-vs-form">4.1 Voicing vs. Form</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Form</strong> = fingering pattern / <strong class="font-semibold">Voicing</strong> = internal arrangement.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Same D chord sounds different depending on whether the <strong class="font-semibold">top note is F# or A</strong>.</p>

<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Keep top notes <strong class="font-semibold">Aâ†’Aâ†’Bâ†’B</strong> through Dâ†’Bmâ†’Gâ†’A.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="inversions">4.2 Inversions and Slash Chords</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Use <strong class="font-semibold">D/F#</strong> or <strong class="font-semibold">A/C#</strong> for smooth bass lines.  </p>
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Dâ†’<strong class="font-semibold">A/C#</strong>â†’Bmâ†’<strong class="font-semibold">G/D</strong> (bass moves Dâ†’C#â†’Bâ†’D in steps).

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="harmonic-rhythm">4.3 Harmonic Rhythm</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Design of chord duration. Verse = 1 bar, chorus = 2 beats creates <strong class="font-semibold">contrast</strong> for drama.  </p>
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Switch to <strong class="font-semibold">2-beat changes</strong> in the second chorus for acceleration.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="color">5. Adding Color</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="secondary">5.1 Secondary Dominants (V/â—‹â—‹)</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Temporarily treat target chord as tonic â†’ approach with its V7.  </p>
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: In D, <strong class="font-semibold">E7â†’A</strong> (V/Vâ†’V).  
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Insert <strong class="font-semibold">E7â†’A</strong> right before the chorus.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="modal-interchange">5.2 Modal Interchange (Borrowed Chords)</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Borrow <strong class="font-semibold">bVII / bVI / iv</strong> from parallel minor.  </p>
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Câ€“G</strong> (Iâ€“bVIIâ€“IV), <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Gmâ€“D</strong> (Iâ€“ivâ€“I).  
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Replace interlude with <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Câ€“Gâ€“D</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="tritone-backdoor">5.3 Tritone Substitution & Backdoor</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">A7â†’D</strong> becomes <strong class="font-semibold">Eâ™­7â†’D</strong>. <strong class="font-semibold">Gâ†’C7â†’D</strong> for gentle resolution.  
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">Eâ™­7â†’D</strong> only at the ending.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3" id="diminished">5.4 Passing Diminished</h3>
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">Insert <strong class="font-semibold">#ivoÂ°7</strong> for one beat to create a chromatic bridge.  </p>
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Dï½œG#Â°7ï½œAï½œD</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">30-Second Recipe</strong>: Add <strong class="font-semibold">just a moment</strong> of #ivoÂ°7 before the chorus.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="recipes">6. Practical Recipes (By Use Case)</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Singer-Songwriter</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Foundation</strong>: Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Technique</strong>: Verse uses open chords, chorus adds 7ths (A7).  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Caution</strong>: Keep low end light, top note close to vocal range.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Two Guitars</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Foundation</strong>: One focuses on roots, the other on 3rd/7th.  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Technique</strong>: When clashing, remove the 5th.  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Caution</strong>: Don't thicken too much in the same register.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Band (With Bass)</h3>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Foundation</strong>: Guitar delegates root duty to bass.  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Technique</strong>: Stay in upper 3â€“4 strings with tight voicings.  </li>
<li><strong class="font-semibold">Caution</strong>: With distortion, reduce 3rds.</li>
</ul>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="troubleshoot">7. Quick Fixes</h2>

<strong class="font-semibold">Muddy/Not Cutting Through</strong>: Low-end overlap. â†’ Remove 5th, prioritize <strong class="font-semibold">3rd/7th + root</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Chorus Too High</strong>: First <strong class="font-semibold">change key (Â±half-step)</strong>, adjust fingering later.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Chord Too Difficult</strong>: Replace with easier chord having <strong class="font-semibold">same function</strong> (A7 â†’ C#Â° / Em/A etc.).

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2" id="faq">8. FAQ</h2>

<strong class="font-semibold">Q. If D is "1", what degree is C?</strong>  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">A. In both D major and D minor, <strong class="font-semibold">C = â™­7</strong>. <strong class="font-semibold">C# = 7</strong>.</p>

<strong class="font-semibold">Q. What does "â™­3" become when the key changes?</strong>  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">A. Always "3 lowered a half-step from 1". C = Eâ™­, D = F, E = G.</p>

<strong class="font-semibold">Q. What's the difference between degrees and Roman numerals?</strong>  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">A. <strong class="font-semibold">Degrees = single note numbers</strong>, <strong class="font-semibold">Roman numerals = chords built on those numbers</strong>.</p>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">What to Read Next</h2>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 mb-4">
<li>Check terms quickly â†’ <a href="/resources/glossary" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/glossary</a>  </li>
<li>Find chord fingerings â†’ (Coming soon) <strong class="font-semibold">Chord Library</strong> <code class="px-1.5 py-0.5 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded text-sm font-mono">/resources/chord-library</code></li>
</ul>



