y\n\n\u003e This page explains **background concepts that couldn't fit in popups**, written in guitarist-friendly language.  \n\u003e Each section ends with a **30-second recipe** for immediate hands-on practice.  \n\u003e Designed to be fully understood **through text alone**, no images or audio needed.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n- [1. Notes and Degrees (Reading in Numbers)](#degrees)\n- [2. Chord Basics (Building by Numbers)](#chords)\n- [3. Keys and Roman Numerals (Transposing by Numbers)](#key-roman)\n- [4. Guitar-Specific (Voicing/Inversions/Rhythm)](#guitarist)\n- [5. Adding Color (Secondary/Borrowed/Substitution)](#color)\n- [6. Practical Recipes (By Use Case)](#recipes)\n- [7. Quick Fixes](#troubleshoot)\n- [8. FAQ](#faq)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Notes and Degrees (Reading in Numbers) {#degrees}\n\n\u003e **Key Point**: Use **1 = tonic** to understand **position relationships through numbers 1â€“7**. When the key changes, \"1\" moves (movable do). The number sequence stays the same.\n\n### 1.1 What Are Degrees (Movable Do System) {#what-are-degrees}\n- C major: **1=C 2=D 3=E 4=F 5=G 6=A 7=B**  \n- D major: **1=D 2=E 3=F# 4=G 5=A 6=B 7=C#**  \n- **â™­/â™¯ in degrees** (e.g., â™­3, â™¯4) indicate \"half-step shifts\".\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Say the **1** of your current key out loud, then translate 1â†’2â†’3â€¦ into note names.\n\n### 1.2 Major vs. Minor Sequences {#major-minor-degrees}\n- **Major**: 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 (wholeâ€“wholeâ€“halfâ€“wholeâ€“wholeâ€“wholeâ€“half)  \n- **Natural Minor**: 1 2 â™­3 4 5 â™­6 â™­7  \n(Harmonic = raised 7, Melodic ascending = raised 6 \u0026 7)\n\n**Example with D as Tonic**  \nD major: D E **F#** G A B **C#**  \nD natural minor: D E **F** G A **Bâ™­** **C**\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Identify what degree the melodic peak is, then place that degree as the top note in your accompaniment.\n\n### 1.3 Câ†”D Conversion Cheat Sheet {#c-d-cheatsheet}\n| Degree | C Major | D Major |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | C | D |\n| 2 | D | E |\n| 3 | E | F# |\n| 4 | F | G |\n| 5 | G | A |\n| 6 | A | B |\n| 7 | B | C# |\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: **Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV (Câ€“Gâ€“Amâ€“F)** in C â†’ **Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G** in D.\n\n### 1.4 Degrees vs. Intervals {#degree-vs-interval}\n- **Degrees**: Numbers within a key (1â€“7)  \n- **Intervals**: Distance between any two notes (perfect 5th, minor 3rd, etc.)  \nâ†’ Use **degrees for progressions/melodies, intervals for voicings**.\n\n### 1.5 Finding Degrees on the Fretboard: Quick Method {#on-fretboard}\n1. Fix **1 (tonic)** on 6th or 5th string (e.g., D = 5th string 5th fret / 6th string 10th fret).  \n2. On the same string: **+2 = 2 â†’ +2 = 3 â†’ +1 = 4 â€¦** (wholeâ€“wholeâ€“halfâ€¦).  \n3. Work backwards from forms that place the desired degree on **top**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Chord Basics (Building by Numbers) {#chords}\n\n### 2.1 Triads {#triads}\n- **Major**: 1â€“3â€“5 (sunny)  \n- **Minor**: 1â€“â™­3â€“5 (cloudy)  \n- **Dim**: 1â€“â™­3â€“â™­5 (anxious)  \n- **Aug**: 1â€“3â€“â™¯5 (floating)\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Play Dâ†’**Dm**â†’G (change just the 3rd by a half-step) to hear the color shift.\n\n### 2.2 Seventh Chords {#sevenths}\n- **V7** = arrow pushing to I (A7â†’D)  \n- **maj7** = dissolves into the same place (Dmaj7)  \n- **m7** = calm depth (Em7)  \n- **m7â™­5** = bridge tension (BÃ¸)\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Play **Aâ†’A7â†’D** to feel the 7th's \"arrow effect\".\n\n### 2.3 Reading Symbols (add/sus/slash) {#symbols}\n- **add9**: Add color  \n- **sus4/sus2**: Suspend 3rd temporarily â†’ resolve back to 3  \n- **D/F#**: Specify bass note (inversion)\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Oscillate **Dâ€“Dsus4â€“D** to experience \"suspension â†’ resolution\".\n\n---\n\n## 3. Keys and Roman Numerals (Transposing by Numbers) {#key-roman}\n\n### 3.1 Diatonic Chords {#diatonic}\n- **D major**: D Em F#m G A Bm C#Â°  \n- **D minor (natural)**: Dm EÂ° F Gm Am (or A) Bâ™­ C\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Transpose **Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV** to D â†’ **Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G**.\n\n### 3.2 Function and Cadences {#tsd}\n- **T (stable)**: I, vi  \n- **S (preparation)**: ii, IV  \n- **D (gravitational pull)**: V, viiÂ°  \n\n**Cadence Examples**:  \nVâ†’I (strong) / IVâ†’I (soft) / Vâ†’vi (deceptive)\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Always use **Vâ†’I** at the start of the chorus to plant a flag.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Guitar-Specific {#guitarist}\n\n### 4.1 Voicing vs. Form {#voicing-vs-form}\n**Form** = fingering pattern / **Voicing** = internal arrangement.  \nSame D chord sounds different depending on whether the **top note is F# or A**.\n\n**30-Second Recipe**: Keep top notes **Aâ†’Aâ†’Bâ†’B** through Dâ†’Bmâ†’Gâ†’A.\n\n### 4.2 Inversions and Slash Chords {#inversions}\nUse **D/F#** or **A/C#** for smooth bass lines.  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Dâ†’**A/C#**â†’Bmâ†’**G/D** (bass moves Dâ†’C#â†’Bâ†’D in steps).\n\n### 4.3 Harmonic Rhythm {#harmonic-rhythm}\nDesign of chord duration. Verse = 1 bar, chorus = 2 beats creates **contrast** for drama.  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Switch to **2-beat changes** in the second chorus for acceleration.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Adding Color {#color}\n\n### 5.1 Secondary Dominants (V/â—‹â—‹) {#secondary}\nTemporarily treat target chord as tonic â†’ approach with its V7.  \n**Example**: In D, **E7â†’A** (V/Vâ†’V).  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Insert **E7â†’A** right before the chorus.\n\n### 5.2 Modal Interchange (Borrowed Chords) {#modal-interchange}\nBorrow **bVII / bVI / iv** from parallel minor.  \n**Example**: **Dâ€“Câ€“G** (Iâ€“bVIIâ€“IV), **Dâ€“Gmâ€“D** (Iâ€“ivâ€“I).  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Replace interlude with **Dâ€“Câ€“Gâ€“D**.\n\n### 5.3 Tritone Substitution \u0026 Backdoor {#tritone-backdoor}\n**A7â†’D** becomes **Eâ™­7â†’D**. **Gâ†’C7â†’D** for gentle resolution.  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Use **Eâ™­7â†’D** only at the ending.\n\n### 5.4 Passing Diminished {#diminished}\nInsert **#ivoÂ°7** for one beat to create a chromatic bridge.  \n**Example**: **Dï½œG#Â°7ï½œAï½œD**.  \n**30-Second Recipe**: Add **just a moment** of #ivoÂ°7 before the chorus.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Practical Recipes (By Use Case) {#recipes}\n\n### Singer-Songwriter\n- **Foundation**: Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV  \n- **Technique**: Verse uses open chords, chorus adds 7ths (A7).  \n- **Caution**: Keep low end light, top note close to vocal range.\n\n### Two Guitars\n- **Foundation**: One focuses on roots, the other on 3rd/7th.  \n- **Technique**: When clashing, remove the 5th.  \n- **Caution**: Don't thicken too much in the same register.\n\n### Band (With Bass)\n- **Foundation**: Guitar delegates root duty to bass.  \n- **Technique**: Stay in upper 3â€“4 strings with tight voicings.  \n- **Caution**: With distortion, reduce 3rds.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Quick Fixes {#troubleshoot}\n\n**Muddy/Not Cutting Through**: Low-end overlap. â†’ Remove 5th, prioritize **3rd/7th + root**.  \n**Chorus Too High**: First **change key (Â±half-step)**, adjust fingering later.  \n**Chord Too Difficult**: Replace with easier chord having **same function** (A7 â†’ C#Â° / Em/A etc.).\n\n---\n\n## 8. FAQ {#faq}\n\n**Q. If D is \"1\", what degree is C?**  \nA. In both D major and D minor, **C = â™­7**. **C# = 7**.\n\n**Q. What does \"â™­3\" become when the key changes?**  \nA. Always \"3 lowered a half-step from 1\". C = Eâ™­, D = F, E = G.\n\n**Q. What's the difference between degrees and Roman numerals?**  \nA. **Degrees = single note numbers**, **Roman numerals = chords built on those numbers**.\n\n---\n\n## What to Read Next\n- Check terms quickly â†’ [/resources/glossary](/resources/glossary)  \n- Find chord fingerings â†’ (Coming soon) **Chord Library** `/resources/chord-library`\n\n\n\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"29:T1e25,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"---\ntitle: \"Music Theory (ç†è«–è§£èª¬)\"\ndescription: \"ã‚®ã‚¿ãƒªã‚¹ãƒˆã®ãŸã‚ã®\"èª­ã‚“ã ã‚‰å¼¾ã‘ã‚‹\"ç†è«–ã€‚åº¦æ•°â†’ã‚³ãƒ¼ãƒ‰â†’é€²è¡Œâ†’è‰²ä»˜ã‘â†’å®Ÿæˆ¦ã®é †ã«æœ€çŸ­ã§å­¦ã¶ã€‚\"\n---\n\n# Music Theoryï¼ˆç†è«–è§£èª¬ï¼‰\n\n\u003e ã“ã®ãƒšãƒ¼ã‚¸ã¯**ãƒãƒƒãƒ—ã‚¢ãƒƒãƒ—ã§æ›¸ãåˆ‡ã‚Œãªã„èƒŒæ™¯**ã‚’ã€ã‚®ã‚¿ãƒªã‚¹ãƒˆå‘ã‘ã®è¨€è‘